# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kde-frameworks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] In computing, a **desktop environment** (**DE**) is an implementation of the desktop metaphor made of a bundle of programs running on top of a computer operating system that share a common graphical user interface (GUI), sometimes described as a graphical shell.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] The desktop environment was seen mostly on personal computers until the rise of mobile computing.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Desktop GUIs help the user to easily access and edit files, while they usually do not provide access to all of the features found in the underlying operating system.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Instead, the traditional command-line interface (CLI) is still used when full control over the operating system is required.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] A desktop environment typically consists of icons, windows, toolbars, folders, wallpapers and desktop widgets (see Elements of graphical user interfaces and WIMP).
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] A GUI might also provide drag and drop functionality and other features that make the desktop metaphor more complete.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] A desktop environment aims to be an intuitive way for the user to interact with the computer using concepts which are similar to those used when interacting with the physical world, such as buttons and windows.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] While the term *desktop environment* originally described a style of user interfaces following the desktop metaphor, it has also come to describe the programs that realize the metaphor itself.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] This usage has been popularized by projects such as the Common Desktop Environment, KDE, and GNOME.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] On a system that offers a desktop environment, a window manager in conjunction with applications written using a widget toolkit are generally responsible for most of what the user sees.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] The window manager supports the user interactions with the environment, while the toolkit provides developers a software library for applications with a unified look and behavior.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] A windowing system of some sort generally interfaces directly with the underlying operating system and libraries.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] This provides support for graphical hardware, pointing devices, and keyboards.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] The window manager generally runs on top of this windowing system.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] While the windowing system may provide some window management functionality, this functionality is still considered to be part of the window manager, which simply happens to have been provided by the windowing system.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Applications that are created with a particular window manager in mind usually make use of a windowing toolkit, generally provided with the operating system or window manager.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] A windowing toolkit gives applications access to widgets that allow the user to interact graphically with the application in a consistent way.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] The first desktop environment was created by Xerox and was sold with the Xerox Alto in the 1970s.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] The Alto was generally considered by Xerox to be a personal office computer; it failed in the marketplace because of poor marketing and a very high price tag.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] With the Lisa, Apple introduced a desktop environment on an affordable personal computer, which also failed in the market.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] The desktop metaphor was popularized on commercial personal computers by the original Macintosh from Apple in 1984, and was popularized further by Windows from Microsoft since the 1990s.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] As of 2014, the most popular desktop environments are descendants of these earlier environments, including the Windows shell used in Microsoft Windows, and the Aqua environment used in macOS.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Microsoft Windows dominates in marketshare among personal computers with a desktop environment.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Computers using Unix-like operating systems such as macOS, ChromeOS, Linux, BSD or Solaris are much less common; however, as of 2015 there is a growing market for low-cost Linux PCs using the X Window System or Wayland with a broad choice of desktop environments.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Among the more popular of these are Google's Chromebooks and Chromeboxes, Intel's NUC, the Raspberry Pi, etc.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] On tablets and smartphones, the situation is the opposite, with Unix-like operating systems dominating the market, including iOS (BSD-derived), Android, Tizen, Sailfish and Ubuntu (all Linux-derived).
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Microsoft's Windows phone, Windows RT and Windows 10 are used on a much smaller number of tablets and smartphones.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] However, the majority of Unix-like operating systems dominant on handheld devices do not use the X11 desktop environments used by other Unix-like operating systems, relying instead on interfaces based on other technologies.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] On systems running the X Window System (typically Unix-family systems such as Linux, the BSDs, and formal UNIX distributions), desktop environments are much more dynamic and customizable to meet user needs.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] In this context, a desktop environment typically consists of several separate components, including a window manager (such as Mutter or KWin), a file manager (such as Files or Dolphin), a set of graphical themes, together with toolkits (such as GTK+ and Qt) and libraries for managing the desktop.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] All these individual modules can be exchanged and independently configured to suit users, but most desktop environments provide a default configuration that works with minimal user setup.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Some window managers‍—‌such as IceWM, Fluxbox, Openbox, ROX Desktop and Window Maker‍—‌contain relatively sparse desktop environment elements, such as an integrated spatial file manager, while others like evilwm and wmii do not provide such elements.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Not all of the program code that is part of a desktop environment has effects which are directly visible to the user.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] KDE, for example, provides so-called KIO slaves which give the user access to a wide range of virtual devices.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] These I/O slaves are not available outside the KDE environment.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] In 1996 the KDE was announced, followed in 1997 by the announcement of GNOME.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Xfce is a smaller project that was also founded in 1996, and focuses on speed and modularity, just like LXDE which was started in 2006.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] A comparison of X Window System desktop environments demonstrates the differences between environments.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] GNOME and KDE were usually seen as dominant solutions, and these are still often installed by default on Linux systems.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] In the early 2000s, KDE reached maturity.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] The Appeal and ToPaZ projects focused on bringing new advances to the next major releases of both KDE and GNOME respectively.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Although striving for broadly similar goals, GNOME and KDE do differ in their approach to user ergonomics.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] KDE encourages applications to integrate and interoperate, is highly customizable, and contains many complex features, all whilst trying to establish sensible defaults.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] GNOME on the other hand is more prescriptive, and focuses on the finer details of essential tasks and overall simplification.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Accordingly, each one attracts a different user and developer community.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Technically, there are numerous technologies common to all Unix-like desktop environments, most obviously the X Window System.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Accordingly, the freedesktop.org project was established as an informal collaboration zone with the goal being to reduce duplication of effort.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] As GNOME and KDE focus on high-performance computers, users of less powerful or older computers often prefer alternative desktop environments specifically created for low-performance systems.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Most commonly used lightweight desktop environments include LXDE and Xfce; they both use GTK+, which is the same underlying toolkit GNOME uses.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] The MATE desktop environment, a fork of GNOME 2, is comparable to Xfce in its use of RAM and processor cycles, but is often considered more as an alternative to other lightweight desktop environments.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] For a while, GNOME and KDE enjoyed the status of the most popular Linux desktop environments; later, other desktop environments grew in popularity.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] In April 2011, GNOME introduced a new interface concept with its version 3, while a popular Linux distribution Ubuntu introduced its own new desktop environment, Unity.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Some users preferred to keep the traditional interface concept of GNOME 2, resulting in the creation of MATE as a GNOME 2 fork.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] The most common desktop environment on personal computers is Windows Shell in Microsoft Windows.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Microsoft has made significant efforts in making Windows shell visually pleasing.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] As a result, Microsoft has introduced theme support in Windows 98, the various Windows XP visual styles, the Aero brand in Windows Vista, the Microsoft design language (codenamed "Metro") in Windows 8, and the Fluent Design System and Windows Spotlight in Windows 10.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Windows shell can be extended via Shell extensions.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Many mainstream desktop environments for Unix-like operating systems, including KDE, GNOME, Xfce, and LXDE, use the X Window System or Wayland, any of which may be selected by users, and are not tied exclusively to the operating system in use.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] The desktop environment for macOS, which is also a Unix-like system, is Aqua, which uses the Quartz graphics layer, rather than using X or Wayland.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] A number of other desktop environments also exist, including (but not limited to) CDE, EDE, GEM, IRIX Interactive Desktop, Sun's Java Desktop System, Jesktop, Mezzo, Project Looking Glass, ROX Desktop, UDE, Xito, XFast.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Moreover, there exists FVWM-Crystal, which consists of a powerful configuration for the FVWM window manager, a theme and further adds, altogether forming a "construction kit" for building up a desktop environment.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] X window managers that are meant to be usable stand-alone — without another desktop environment — also include elements reminiscent of those found in typical desktop environments, most prominently Enlightenment.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Other examples include OpenBox, Fluxbox, WindowLab, Fvwm, as well as Window Maker and AfterStep, which both feature the NeXTSTEP GUI look and feel.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] The Amiga approach to desktop environment was noteworthy: the original Workbench desktop environment in AmigaOS evolved through time to originate an entire family of descendants and alternative desktop solutions.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Some of those descendants are the Scalos, the Ambient desktop of MorphOS, and the Wanderer desktop of the AROS open source OS.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] WindowLab also contains features reminiscent of the Amiga UI.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Third-party Directory Opus software, which was originally just a navigational file manager program, evolved to become a complete Amiga desktop replacement called Directory Opus Magellan.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] OS/2 (and derivatives such as eComStation and ArcaOS) use the Workplace Shell.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Earlier versions of OS/2 used the Presentation Manager.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] The BumpTop project was an experimental desktop environment.
[src:kde-frameworks/desktop-environment] Its main objective is to replace the 2D paradigm with a "real-world" 3D implementation, where documents can be freely manipulated across a virtual table.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] KDE Frameworks is based on Qt, which enables a more widespread use of QML, a simpler JavaScript-based declarative programming language, for the design of user interfaces.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] The graphics rendering engine used by QML allows for more fluid user interfaces across different devices.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Since the split of the KDE Software Compilation into KDE Frameworks 5, KDE Plasma 5 and KDE Applications, each sub-project can pick its own development pace.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] KDE Frameworks are released on a monthly basis and use Git.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] It should be possible to install KDE Frameworks alongside the KDE Platform 4 so apps can use either one.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Platform releases are those which begin a series (version number X.0).
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Only these major releases are allowed to break binary compatibility with the predecessor.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Releases in the minor series (X.1, X.2, ...) will guarantee binary portability (API & ABI).
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] This means, for instance, that software that was developed for KDE 3.0 will work on all (future) KDE 3 releases; however, an application developed for KDE 2 is not guaranteed to be able to make use of the KDE 3 libraries.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] KDE major version numbers mainly follow the Qt release cycle, meaning that KDE SC 4 is based on Qt 4, while KDE 3 was based on Qt 3.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] The repository of each framework should contain a file named *metainfo.yaml*.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] This file documents the maintainer of the framework, the type, the supported operating system and other information.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] The currently supported platforms are Linux, Microsoft Windows, macOS and Android.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] The Frameworks have a clear dependency structure, divided into "categories" and "tiers".
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] The KDE Frameworks bundle consists of over 70 packages.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] These existed as a single large package, called kdelibs, in KDE SC 4.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Kdelibs was split into several individual frameworks, some of which are no longer part of KDE but were integrated into Qt 5.2.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] KDE Frameworks are grouped in four different tiers according to dependency on other libraries.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Depends on Tier 1, but dependencies are still manageable.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Can be mostly ignored by application programmers.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Mostly plugins that provide additional features like platform support.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Kirigami is a QML application framework developed by Marco Martin that enables developers to write applications that run natively on Android, iOS, Windows, Plasma Mobile and any classic Linux desktop environment without code adjustments.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] It is used by various applications, for example Linus Torvalds and Dirk Hohndels' scuba diving application Subsurface, the messenger client Banji, the Kaidan messenger, Vvave music player and the KDE software center Discover.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Linux distribution use some package management system to package the software they distribute.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Debian for example distributes *KGlobalAccel* under the package name *libkf5globalaccel*, while Fedora Linux distributes it under the name *kf5-kglobalaccel*.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] The 5.0 release was preceded by a technology preview, two alpha releases, and three beta releases.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] The source code of KDE Frameworks has been around since KDElibs 1.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] The first release as *KDE Frameworks* was with version 5, to account for the fact that the code base was that of KDE Platform version 4 (the only major version of KDE Platform).
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] The transition from KDE Platform to KDE Frameworks began in August 2013, guided by top KDE technical contributors.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] After the initial release of KDE Frameworks 5.0, the developers focused on adding new features to the components in KDE Frameworks 5, an example being better integration of Firefox into KDE.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] The major improvement of Frameworks 5 is its modularization.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] In earlier KDE versions, the libraries were bundled as a single large package.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] In Frameworks, the libraries were split into individual smaller packages.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] This facilitates utilization of the libraries by other Qt-based software, since dependencies can be kept at a minimum.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] While KDE 4 was based on version 4 of the Qt widget toolkit, Frameworks 5 is based on version 5.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] As part of the KDE project's 'MegaRelease 6', on February 28, 2024, KDE Frameworks 6 was released, upgrading it to a Qt 6 base.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] During KDE SC 4, the then so called KDE Platform consisted of all libraries and services needed for KDE Plasma and the applications.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Starting with Qt 5, this platform was transformed into a set of modules that is now referred to as KDE Frameworks.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] These modules include: Solid, Nepomuk, Phonon, etc. and are licensed either under the LGPL, BSD license, MIT License or X11 license.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Besides the KDE Software Compilation, there are other adopters such as the desktop environments LXQt, MoonLightDE or Hawaii.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] Version 3.0 of Krita, the raster graphics editor of the Calligra Suite, which was released on May 31, 2016, depends on KDE Frameworks 5 and Qt 5.2.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-frameworks] With Kirigami, there is also increased usage by applications such as Amarok, Avogadro, Trojitá or Subsurface.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Plasma was first introduced in 2008 as part of KDE Software Compilation 4, as a major technical overhaul, combining traditional desktop functionality with a widget-based system designed for flexibility and visual consistency.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] With the KDE brand repositioning in 2009, the KDE software compilation was split into three distinct projects: KDE Plasma, KDE Frameworks and KDE Gear, allowing each to develop and release on independent schedules.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] As of the Plasma 6 series, feature updates are released every four months, with interim bugfix releases.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Plasma 4 was released as part of KDE Software Compilation 4 and replacing the KDesktop shell, Kicker taskbar, and SuperKaramba widget engine, which formed the Desktop in earlier KDE releases.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] They are bundled as the default environment with a number of free software operating systems, such as Chakra, Kubuntu, Mageia (DVD version), openSUSE, or TrueOS.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] From KDE SC 4.0 to KDE SC 4.2, the default theme, "Oxygen", was characterized by dark tones.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] In KDE SC 4.3, it was replaced by the new "Air" theme, which predominates in transparency and white as the base color.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] New themes for Plasma can be chosen and installed through software like Discover or online at store.kde.org.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] With the release of KDE SC 4.11 on 14 August 2013, Plasma 4 was placed into a feature freeze and turned into a long-term stable package until August 2015.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] On 15 July 2014, Plasma 4's successor, Plasma 5, was released.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Plasma features *containments*, which are essentially applets that contain other applets.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Two examples of containments are the desktop background and the taskbar.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] A containment can be anything the developer wants: an image (either raster graphics or an SVG image), animation, or even OpenGL.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Images are most commonly used, but with Plasma the user could set any applet as the desktop background without losing functionality of the applet.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] This also allows for applets to be dragged between the desktop and the taskbar (two separate containments), and have a separate visualization for the more confined taskbar.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Plasma separates components into "data engine" and their visualization counterparts.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] This is intended to reduce the total programming effort when there are multiple possible visualizations of given data, and to make it easier for the data engine and the workspaces to be written independently.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] The scalable nature of the Plasma widgets allows for them to be resized and rotated to any size, with only a brief pause to redraw themselves.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] The Kross scripting framework allows developers to write widgets in a variety of programming languages in addition to C++.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] This is a list of widgets that the current release version of Plasma supports.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Not all widgets are supported by default in all Linux distributions; some may require different packages or even a recompilation of Plasma.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Previous Plasma Workspaces releases also supported Edje gadgets and E17 modules.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Support for those was developed in 2008 but removed later, in 2010.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] After Google announced the discontinuation of its two services that utilize Gadgets – Google Desktop and iGoogle – KDE removed support for this widget engine in March 2013.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Plasma 5 is the fifth generation of the graphical workspaces environment created by KDE primarily for Linux systems.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Plasma 5 is the successor of Plasma 4 and was first released on 15 July 2014.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] It includes a new default theme, known as "Breeze", as well as increased convergence across different devices.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] The graphical interface was fully migrated to QML, which uses OpenGL for hardware acceleration, resulting in better performance and reduced power consumption.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Plasma Mobile is a Plasma 5 variant for Linux-based smartphones.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] KDE Plasma 5 is built using Qt 5 and KDE Frameworks 5, predominantly plasma-framework.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] It improves support for HiDPI displays and ships a convergable graphical shell, which can adjust itself according to the device in use.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] 5.0 also includes a new default theme, dubbed Breeze.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Qt 5's QtQuick 2 uses a hardware-accelerated OpenGL(ES) scene graph (canvas) to compose and render graphics on the screen, which allows for the offloading of computationally expensive graphics rendering tasks onto the GPU, freeing up resources on the system's main CPU.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] KDE Plasma 5 uses the X Window System and Wayland.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Support for Wayland was prepared in the compositor and planned for a later release.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] It was made initially available in the 5.4 release.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Stable support for a basic Wayland session was provided in the 5.5 release (December 2015).
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Support for NVIDIA proprietary driver for Plasma on Wayland was added in the 5.16 release (June 2019).
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] KDE Plasma 6 is the sixth and current generation of the graphical workspaces environment made by KDE.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] It is the successor to Plasma 5 and was initially released on 28 February 2024.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Plasma 6 changes the default display server from X11 to Wayland, though the former is still available.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] As of version 6.4, the X11 version is no longer installed by default and the KWin (the KDE window manager) codebase is split into *kwin* and *kwin_x11*.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] *Kwin* is the default Wayland version and will see active development.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] New fixes are developed for *kwin* first and backported later to *kwin_x11*.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Version *kwin_x11* is maintained until Plasma 6.8 and no new features are expected to be backported.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] With the release of Plasma 6 as part of the KDE MegaRelease 6 (28 February 2024), Wayland became the default display protocol, although X11 remains available as an alternative.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde-plasma] Plasma 6.8, scheduled for release on October 2026, is planned to drop the X11 session entirely, with only XWayland remaining to support X11 applications.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] KDE was founded in 1996 by Matthias Ettrich, a student at the University of Tübingen.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] At the time, he was troubled by certain aspects of the Unix desktop.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Among his concerns was that none of the applications looked or behaved alike.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] In his opinion, desktop applications of the time were too complicated for end users.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] In order to solve the issue, he proposed the creation of a desktop environment in which users could expect the applications to be consistent and easy to use.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] His initial Usenet post spurred significant interest, and the KDE project was born.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The name *KDE* was intended as a wordplay on the existing Common Desktop Environment, available for Unix systems.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] CDE was an X11-based user environment jointly developed by HP, IBM, and Sun through the X/Open consortium, with an interface and productivity tools based on the Motif graphical widget toolkit.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] It was supposed to be an intuitively easy-to-use desktop computer environment.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The *K* was originally suggested to stand for "Kool", but it was quickly decided that the *K* should stand for nothing in particular.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Therefore, the *KDE* initialism expanded to *"K Desktop Environment"* before it was dropped altogether in favor of simply *KDE* in a rebranding in 2009.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The KDE community's mascot is a green dragon named Konqi.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Konqi's appearance was officially redesigned with the coming of Plasma 5, with Tyson Tan's entry winning the redesign competition on the KDE Forums.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] In the beginning Matthias Ettrich chose to use Trolltech's Qt framework for the KDE project.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Other programmers quickly started developing KDE/Qt applications, and by early 1997, a few applications were being released.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] On 12 July 1998 the first version of the desktop environment, called KDE 1.0, was released.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The original GNU General Public Licensed version of this toolkit only existed for platforms that used the X11 display server, but as of the release of Qt 4, GNU Lesser General Public Licensed versions are available for more platforms.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] This allowed KDE software based on Qt 4 or newer versions to be distributed to Microsoft Windows and OS X.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The KDE Marketing Team announced a rebranding of the KDE project components on 24 November 2009.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Motivated by the perceived shift in objectives, the rebranding focused on emphasizing both the community of software creators and the various tools supplied by the KDE, rather than just the desktop environment.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] KDE 4 was split into KDE Plasma Workspaces, KDE Applications, and KDE Frameworks (KDE Platform 4 at the time), bundled as KDE Software Compilation 4.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Since 2009, the name *KDE* no longer stands for *K Desktop Environment*, but for the community that produces the software.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The financial and legal matters of KDE are handled by KDE e.V., a German non-profit organization.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Among others, it owns the *KDE* trademark and the corresponding logo.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] It also accepts donations on behalf of the KDE community, helps to run the servers, assists in organizing and financing conferences and meetings, but does not influence software development directly.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] In many countries, KDE has local branches.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] These are either informal organizations (KDE India) or like the KDE e.V., given a legal form (KDE France).
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The local organizations host and maintain regional websites, and organize local events, such as tradeshows, contributor meetings and social community meetings.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] KDE has community identity guidelines (CIG) for definitions and recommendations which help the community to establish a unique, characteristic, and appealing design.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The KDE official logo displays the white trademarked K-Gear shape on a blue square with mitred corners.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Copying of the KDE Logo is subject to the LGPL.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Some local community logos are derivations of the official logo.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Many KDE applications have a *K* in the name, mostly as an initial letter.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The *K* in many KDE applications is obtained by spelling a word which originally begins with *C* or *Q* differently, for example Konsole and Kaffeine, while some others prefix a commonly used word with a *K*, for instance KGet.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] However, some apps do not to have a *K* in the name at all, such as with Stage, Spectacle, Discover and Dolphin.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The KDE community maintains multiple free-software projects.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] KDE neon is a Linux distribution that uses Ubuntu LTS as a core.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] It aims to provide the users with rapidly updated Qt and KDE software, while updating the rest of the OS components from the Ubuntu repositories at the normal pace.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Subtitle Composer is an open-source subtitle editor for the Linux and Microsoft Windows operating systems, based on Qt and KDE Frameworks.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The project became part of KDE starting in December 2019.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] It supports the most common text and bitmap-based subtitle formats, video previewing, audio waveform, speech recognition, timings synchronization, subtitle translation, OCR and JavaScript macros/scripting.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Subtitle Composer is free software released under the GNU General Public License.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Developing KDE software is primarily a volunteer effort, although various companies, such as Novell, Nokia, or Blue Systems employ or employed developers to work on various parts of the project.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Since a large number of individuals contribute to KDE in various ways (e.g. code, translation, artwork), organization of such a project is complex.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] A mentor program helps beginners to get started with developing and communicating within KDE projects and communities.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Communication within the community takes place via mailing lists, IRC, blogs, forums, news announcements, wikis and conferences.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The community has a Code of Conduct for acceptable behavior within the community.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Currently the KDE community uses the Git version control system.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The KDE GitLab Instance (named Invent) gives an overview of all projects hosted by KDE's Git repository system.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Phabricator is used for task management.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] On 20 July 2009, KDE announced that the one millionth commit has been made to its Subversion repository.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] On 11 October 2009, Cornelius Schumacher, a main developer within KDE, wrote about the estimated cost (using the COCOMO model with SLOCCount) to develop KDE software package with 4,273,291 LoC, which would be about US$175,364,716.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] This estimation does not include Qt, Calligra Suite, Amarok, digiKam, and other applications that are not part of KDE core.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The overall direction is set by the *KDE Core Team*.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] These are developers who have made significant contributions within KDE over a long period of time.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] This team communicates using the *kde-core-devel* mailing list, which is publicly archived and readable, but joining requires approval.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] KDE does not have a single central leader who can veto important decisions.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Instead, the KDE core team consists of several dozens of contributors who make decisions not by a formal vote, but through discussions.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The developers also organize alongside topical teams.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] For example, the *KDE Edu team* develops free educational software.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] While these teams work mostly independent and do not all follow a common release schedule.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Each team has its own messaging channels, both on IRC and on the mailing lists.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] A KDE Patron is an individual or organization supporting the KDE community by donating at least 5000 Euro (depending on the company's size) to the KDE e.V.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] As of March 2026, there are thirteen such patrons: Blue Systems, Canonical Ltd., Google, GnuPG, Kubuntu Focus, Slimbook, SUSE, The Qt Company, TUXEDO Computers, Rocky Linux, Framework Computer, Techpaladin Software, and Mbition.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] On 23 June 2005, chairman of the Wikimedia Foundation announced that the KDE community and the Wikimedia Foundation have begun efforts towards cooperation.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Fruits of that cooperation are MediaWiki syntax highlighting in Kate and accessing Wikipedia content within KDE applications, such as Amarok and Marble.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] On 4 April 2008, the KDE e.V. and Wikimedia Deutschland opened shared offices in Frankfurt.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] In May 2006, KDE e.V. became an Associate Member of the Free Software Foundation Europe (FSFE).
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] On 22 August 2008, KDE e.V. and FSFE jointly announced that after working with FSFE's Freedom Task Force for one and a half years KDE adopts FSFE's Fiduciary Licence Agreement.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Using that, KDE developers can – on a voluntary basis – assign their copyrights to KDE e.V.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] In September 2009, KDE e.V. and FSFE moved into shared offices in Berlin.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Several companies actively contribute to KDE, like Collabora, Erfrakon, Intevation GmbH, Kolab Konsortium, Klarälvdalens Datakonsult AB (KDAB), Blue Systems, and KO GmbH.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Nokia used Calligra Suite as base for their *Office Viewer* application for Maemo/MeeGo.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] They have also been contracting KO GmbH to bring MS Office 2007 file format filters to Calligra.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Nokia also employed several KDE developers directly – either to use KDE software for MeeGo (e.g.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The software development and consulting companies Intevation GmbH of Germany and the Swedish KDAB use Qt and KDE software – especially Kontact and Akonadi for Kolab – for their services and products, therefore both employ KDE developers.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] KDE participates in freedesktop.org, an effort to standardize Unix desktop interoperability.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] In 2009 and 2011, GNOME and KDE co-hosted their conferences Akademy and GUADEC under the *Desktop Summit* label.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] In December 2010 KDE e.V. became a licensee of the Open Invention Network.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Many Linux distributions and other free operating systems are involved in the development and distribution of the software, and are therefore also active in the KDE community.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] These include commercial distributors such as SUSE/Novell or Red Hat but also government-funded non-commercial organizations such as the Scientific and Technological Research Council of Turkey with its Linux distribution Pardus.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] In October 2018, Red Hat declared that KDE Plasma was no longer supported in future updates of Red Hat Enterprise Linux, though it continues to be part of Fedora.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The announcement came shortly after the announcement of the business acquisition of Red Hat by IBM for close to US$43 billion.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] As a result, Fedora now makes KDE Plasma and other KDE software available also to Red Hat Enterprise Linux users through their Extra Packages for Enterprise Linux (EPEL) project.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The two most important conferences of KDE are *Akademy* and *Camp KDE*.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Each event is on a large scale, both thematically and geographically.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] *Akademy-BR* and *Akademy-es* are local community events.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The first conference that the KDE community held was KDE One, in Arnsberg, Germany, in 1997 to discuss the first KDE release.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Initially, each conference was numbered after the release, and not regular held.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Since 2003 the conferences were held once a year.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The yearly Akademy conference gives *Akademy Awards*, are awards that the KDE community gives to KDE contributors.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Their purpose is to recognize outstanding contribution to KDE.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] There are three awards, best application, best non-application and jury's award.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] As always the winners are chosen by the winners from the previous year.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] First winners received a framed picture of Konqi signed by all attending KDE developers.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] In January 2008, KDE 4.0 Release Event was held at the Google headquarters in Mountain View, California, US, to celebrate the release of KDE SC 4.0.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The community realized that there was a strong demand for KDE events in the Americas, therefore Camp KDE was produced.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Camp KDE 2009 was the premiere meeting of the KDE Americas, was held at the Travellers Beach Resort in Negril, Jamaica, sponsored by Google, Intel, iXsystem, KDE e.V. and Kitware.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The event included 1–2 days of presentations, BoF meetings and hackathon sessions.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Camp KDE 2010 took place at the University of California, San Diego (UCSD) in La Jolla, US.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The schedule included presentations, BoFs, hackathons and a day trip.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] It started with a short introduction by Jeff Mitchell, who was the principal organizer of the conference, talked a bit of history about Camp KDE and some statistics about the KDE community.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] With around 70 participants, the talks of the event were relatively well attended.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] On 1/19, the social event was a tour of a local brewery.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Camp KDE 2011 was held at Hotel Kabuki in San Francisco, US.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] It was co-located with the Linux Foundation Collaboration Summit.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The schedule included presentations, hackathons and a party at Noisebridge.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The conference opened with an introduction by Celeste Lyn Paul.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Season of KDE is an outreach program hosted by the KDE community.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Students are appointed mentors from the KDE community that help bring their project to fruition.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] conf.kde.in was the first KDE and Qt conference in India.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The conference, organized by KDE India, was held at R.V.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] College of Engineering in Bangalore, India.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The first three days of the event had talks, tutorials, and interactive sessions.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The last two days were a focused code sprint.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The conference was opened by its main organizer, Pradeepto Bhattacharya.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Over 300 people were at the opening talks.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The Lighting of the Auspicious Lamp ceremony was performed to open the conference.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The first session was by Lydia Pintscher, who spoke on "So much to do – so little time".
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] At the event, the return of Project Neon was announced on March 11, 2011, with the project providing nightly builds of the KDE Software Compilation.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Closing the conference was keynote speaker and old-time KDE developer Sirtaj.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] A *Release party* is a party, which celebrates the release of a new version of the KDE SC (twice a year).
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] KDE also participates in other conferences that revolve around free software.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Brazil's primary school education system operates computers running KDE software, with more than 42,000 schools in 4,000 cities, thus serving nearly 52 million children.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] The base distribution is called Educational Linux, which is based on Kubuntu.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Besides this, thousands more students in Brazil use KDE products in their universities.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] KDE software is also running on computers in Portuguese and Venezuelan schools, with respectively 700,000 and one million systems reached.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] CERN (European Organization for Nuclear Research) uses KDE software.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Germany uses KDE software in its embassies around the world, representing around 11,000 systems.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] NASA used the Plasma Desktop during the Mars Mission.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] Valve Corporation's handheld gaming computer, the Steam Deck, uses the KDE Plasma desktop environment when in desktop mode.
[src:kde-frameworks/kde] In 2025, Valve Corporation has revealed that their upcoming compact gaming computer, the Steam Machine, and virtual reality headset, named the Steam Frame, will also be using the KDE Plasma desktop environment when in desktop mode.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt is currently being developed by The Qt Company, a publicly listed company, and the Qt Project under open-source governance, involving individual developers and organizations working to advance Qt.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt is available under both commercial licenses and open-source GPL 2.0, GPL 3.0, and LGPL 3.0 licenses.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt is used for developing graphical user interfaces (GUIs) and multi-platform applications that run on all major desktop platforms and mobile or embedded platforms.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Most GUI programs created with Qt have a native-looking interface, in which case Qt is classified as a *widget toolkit*.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Non-GUI programs can also be developed, such as command-line tools and consoles for servers.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] An example of such a non-GUI program using Qt is the Cutelyst web framework.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt supports various C++ compilers, including the GCC and Clang C++ compilers and the Visual Studio suite.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] It supports other languages with bindings or extensions, such as Python via Python bindings and PHP via an extension for PHP5, and has extensive internationalization support.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt also provides Qt Quick, that includes a declarative scripting language called QML that allows using JavaScript to provide the logic.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] With Qt Quick, rapid application development for mobile devices became possible, while logic can still be written with native code as well to achieve the best possible performance.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Other features include SQL database access, XML parsing, JSON parsing, thread management and network support.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The latest version of the Qt Framework is Qt 6.11, which was released on 23 March 2026.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Also still supported are versions 6.10 until 7 October 2026 and 6.8 LTS until 8 October 2029.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Version 6.5 LTS is supported for commercial users only until 3 April 2026.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Additionally, extended support for all versions 5.0 (released in 2012) and newer is available for commercial users.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Minor versions of Qt are typically released twice a year and are supported until one year after release date under standard support conditions.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Typically, every third minor version becomes a long-term support version which gets additional patches.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] LTS versions are supported for commercial users until five years after their release date (three years prior to version 6.8).
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] In 2017, the Qt Company estimated a community of about 1 million developers worldwide in over 70 industries.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] When first released, Qt used its own paint engine and controls, emulating the look of the different platforms it runs on when it drew its widgets.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] This made the porting work easier because very few classes in Qt really depended on the target platform; however, this occasionally led to slight discrepancies where that emulation was imperfect.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Recent versions of Qt use the native style APIs of the different platforms, on platforms that have a native widget set, to query metrics and draw most controls, and do not suffer from such issues as often.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] On some platforms (such as MeeGo and KDE) Qt *is* the native API.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Some other portable graphical toolkits have made different design decisions; for example, wxWidgets uses the toolkits of the target platform for its implementations.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Signals and slots are a language construct introduced in Qt for communication between objects which makes it easy to implement the observer pattern while avoiding boilerplate code.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The concept is that GUI widgets can send signals containing event information which can be received by other controls using special functions known as slots.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The metaobject compiler, termed *moc*, is a tool that is run on the sources of a Qt program.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] It interprets certain macros from the C++ code as annotations, and uses them to generate added C++ code with meta information about the classes used in the program.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] This meta information is used by Qt to provide programming features not available natively in C++: signals and slots, introspection and asynchronous function calls.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt moc does not recognise modules in its preprocessor currently.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt can be used in several programming languages other than C++, such as Python, JavaScript, C# and Rust via language bindings; many languages have bindings for Qt 5 and bindings for Qt 4.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] In 2025 The Qt Company announced a new "bridging technology" that aimed to re-think the way of interacting with new languages, listing that a proof of concept was being worked on for integrating C#, Rust, Swift, Java/Kotlin, and Python.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Starting with Qt 4.0 the framework was split into individual modules.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] With Qt 5.0 the architecture was modularized even further.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt is now split into *essential* and *add-on* modules.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt classes by default do not reside in any namespace, but all classes are prefixed with the letter Q.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt can be configured to be compiled to reside in a user-defined namespace.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt is entirely provided through header files, and does not currently support C++ modules.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] There are four editions of Qt available: *Community*, *Indie Mobile*, *Professional* and *Enterprise*.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The Community version is under the open source licenses, while the Indie Mobile, Professional and Enterprise versions, which contain additional functionality and libraries, e.g.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Enterprise Controls are commercially sold by The Qt Company.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] After Nokia opened the Qt source code to the community on Gitorious, various ports appeared.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] There are also some ports of Qt that may be available, but are not supported anymore.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] These platforms are listed in List of platforms supported by Qt.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] See also there for current community support for other lesser known platforms, such as SailfishOS.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt is available under the following free software licenses: GPL 2.0, GPL 3.0, LGPL 3.0 and LGPL 2.1 (with Qt special exception).
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Note that some modules are available only under a GPL license, which means that applications which link to these modules need to comply with that license.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] In addition, Qt has always been available under a commercial license, like the Qt Commercial License, that allows developing proprietary applications with no restrictions on licensing.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt comes with its own set of tools to ease cross-platform development, which can otherwise be cumbersome due to different set of development tools.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt Creator is a cross-platform IDE for C++ and QML.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt Designer's GUI layout/design functionality is integrated into the IDE, although Qt Designer can still be started as a standalone tool.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] In addition to Qt Creator, Qt provides qmake, a cross-platform build script generation tool that automates the generation of Makefiles for development projects across different platforms.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] There are other tools available in Qt, including the Qt Designer interface builder and the Qt Assistant help browser (which are both embedded in Qt Creator), the Qt Linguist translation tool, uic (user interface compiler), and moc (Meta-Object Compiler).
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] In the summer of 1990, Haavard Nord and Eirik Chambe-Eng (the original developers of Qt and the CEO and President, respectively, of The Qt Company) were working together on a database application for ultrasound images written in C++ and running on the classic Mac OS, Unix, and Microsoft Windows.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] They began development of "Qt" in 1991, three years before the company was incorporated as Quasar Technologies, then changed the name to Troll Tech and then to Trolltech.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The toolkit was called Qt because the letter Q looked appealing in Haavard's Emacs typeface, and "t" was inspired by Xt, the X toolkit.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The first two versions of Qt had only two flavors: Qt/X11 for Unix and Qt/Windows for Windows.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] On 20 May 1995 Trolltech publicly released Qt 0.90 for X11/Linux with the source code under the *Qt Free Edition License*.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] This license was viewed as not compliant with the free software definition by Free Software Foundation because, while the source was available, it did not allow the redistribution of modified versions.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Trolltech used this license until version 1.45.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Controversy erupted around 1998 when it became clear that the K Desktop Environment was going to become one of the leading desktop environments for Linux.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] As it was based on Qt, many people in the free software movement worried that an essential piece of one of their major operating systems would be proprietary.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The Windows platform was available only under a proprietary license, which meant free/open source applications written in Qt for X11 could not be ported to Windows without purchasing the proprietary edition.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] With the release of version 2.0 of the toolkit in mid-1999, the license was changed to the Q Public License (QPL), a free software license, but one regarded by the Free Software Foundation as incompatible with the GPL.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Compromises were sought between KDE and Trolltech whereby Qt would not be able to fall under a more restrictive license than the QPL, even if Trolltech was bought out or went bankrupt.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] This led to the creation of the KDE Free Qt foundation, which guarantees that Qt would fall under a BSD-style license should no free/open source version of Qt be released during 12 months.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] In 2000, Qt/X11 2.2 was released under the GPL v2, ending all controversy regarding GPL compatibility.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] At the end of 2001, Trolltech released Qt 3.0, which added support for Mac OS X (now known as macOS).
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The Mac OS X support was available only in the proprietary license until June 2003, when Trolltech released Qt 3.2 with Mac OS X support available under the GPL.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] In 2002, members of the KDE on Cygwin project began porting the GPL licensed Qt/X11 code base to Windows.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] This was in response to Trolltech's refusal to license Qt/Windows under the GPL on the grounds that Windows was not a free/open source software platform.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The project achieved some success although it never reached production quality.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] This was resolved when Trolltech released Qt 4.0 also for Windows under the GPL in June 2005.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt 4 supported the same set of platforms in the free software/open source editions as in the proprietary edition, so it is possible, with Qt 4.0 and later releases, to create GPL-licensed free/open source applications using Qt on all supported platforms.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The GPL v3 with special exception was later added as an added licensing option.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The GPL exception allows the final application to be licensed under various GPL-incompatible free software/open source licenses such as the Mozilla Public License 1.1.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Nokia acquired Trolltech ASA on 17 June 2008 and changed the name first to Qt Software, then to Qt Development Frameworks.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Nokia focused on turning Qt into the main development platform for its devices, including a port to the Symbian S60 platform.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Version 1.0 of the Nokia Qt SDK was released on 23 June 2010.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The source code was made available over Gitorious, a community oriented git source code repository, with a goal of creating a broader community using and improving Qt.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] On 14 January 2009, Qt version 4.5 added another option, the LGPL, to make Qt more attractive for both non-GPL open source projects and closed applications.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] In February 2011, Nokia announced its decision to discontinue Symbian technologies and base their future smartphones on the Windows Phone platform instead (and since then support for that platform has also been dropped).
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] In March 2011, Nokia sold the commercial licensing part of Qt to Digia, creating Qt Commercial.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] In August 2012, Digia announced that it would acquire Qt from Nokia.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The Qt team at Digia started their work in September 2012.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] They released Qt 5.0 within a month and newer versions every six months with new features and additional supported platforms.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] In September 2014, Digia transferred the Qt business and copyrights to their wholly owned subsidiary, The Qt Company, which owns 25 brands related to Qt.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] In May 2016, Digia and Qt demerged completely into two independent companies.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt 5 was officially released on 19 December 2012.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] This new version marked a major change in the platform, with hardware-accelerated graphics, QML and JavaScript playing a major role.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] The traditional C++-only QWidgets continued to be supported, but did not benefit from the performance improvements available through the new architecture.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Qt 5 brings significant improvements to the speed and ease of developing user interfaces.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Framework development of Qt 5 moved to open governance at qt-project.org, which made it possible for developers outside Digia to submit patches for review.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Aside from The Qt Company, many organizations and individuals using Qt as their development platform participate in the open development of Qt via the Qt Project.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] One such Qt contributor is Klarälvdalens Datakonsult AB, a Swedish Qt consulting company.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] KDAB is involved in many areas, including maintenance of several components.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Together with RIM/BlackBerry, KDAB is maintaining the QNX and BlackBerry 10 ports of Qt.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] Another participator is Intel, contributing for example Wayland support.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] AudioCodes maintains IBM ClearCase support in Qt Creator.
[src:kde-frameworks/qt-software] As a heavy user of Qt, the KDE project submits many patches and features from its developer library KDE Frameworks back to Qt.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] A **widget toolkit**, **widget library**, **GUI toolkit**, **GUI framework**, **UI framework**, or **UX library** is a library or a collection of libraries containing a set of graphical control elements (called *widgets*) used to construct the graphical user interface (GUI) of programs.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] Most widget toolkits additionally include their own rendering engine.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] This engine can be specific to a certain operating system or windowing system or contain back-ends to interface with multiple ones and also with rendering APIs such as OpenGL, OpenVG, or EGL.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] The look and feel of the graphical control elements can be hard-coded or decoupled, allowing the graphical control elements to be themed/skinned.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] Some toolkits may be used from other languages by employing language bindings.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] Graphical user interface builders such as e.g.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] Glade Interface Designer facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language such as in this case GtkBuilder.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] The GUI of a program is commonly constructed in a cascading manner, with graphical control elements being added directly to on top of one another.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] Most widget toolkits use event-driven programming as a model for interaction.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] The toolkit handles user events, for example when the user clicks on a button.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] When an event is detected, it is passed on to the application where it is dealt with.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] The design of those toolkits has been criticized for promoting an oversimplified model of event-action, leading programmers to create error-prone, difficult to extend and excessively complex application code.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] Finite-state machines and hierarchical state machines have been proposed as high-level models to represent the interactive state changes for reactive programs.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] A window is considered to be a graphical control element.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] In some windowing systems, windows are added directly to the scene graph (canvas) by the window manager, and can be stacked and layered on top of each other through various means.
[src:kde-frameworks/widget-toolkit] Each window is associated with a particular application which controls the widgets added to its canvas, which can be watched and modified by their associated applications.
